<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 4:10<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If280ea316b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="Ib978dbb0933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>4.</label.designator><headtext>Procedure Before the Panel</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94ee1e3ae1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>4:10.</label.designator><headtext>Initiating Panel proceedings—Page limit</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel Rules impose a 20-page limit on the length of any brief submitted to the Panel.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If28111406b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] A longer brief may be filed only with the permission of the Panel in the case of &quot;exceptional circumstances.&quot;[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If28111426b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>] This requirement is similar to brief-length requirements imposed in many courts.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If28111436b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>] The Panel has not resorted to the word-count approach to size used in the rules of appellate procedure. <eos/><bos/>This should not be viewed as a license to “stuff” a 30-page brief onto 20 pages of paper, however.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If28111446b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>] Reply briefs are limited to 10 pages and to addressing arguments raised in a response.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If28138506b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">5</footnote.reference>] The Panel rules to specify that a 12-point font must be used for both text and footnotes.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If28138516b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If280ea316b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If28111406b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>J.P.M.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913977" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR3.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I5551cf406b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 3.2(a)(iii)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The Panel rules are reproduced in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs4:34" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If28111416b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 4:34</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If28111426b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>Id.<eos/><bos/></ital> The rule indicates that a motion requires “exceptional circumstances” and Panel practice is not to grant these motions. <eos/><bos/>Obviously, the mere fact that the case is important, or involves many parties or complex issues, is not “exceptional,” as these characteristics are routine in the matters before the Panel.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If28111436b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Page limits for briefs are discussed in <csc>David F. Herr, Roger S. Haydock &amp; Jeffrey W. Stempel, Motion Practice</csc>§§ 5.4 and 5.5 (76th ed. 2016).<eos/><bos/> Local rules limiting the length of briefs are collected in <ital>id.<eos/><bos/></ital> § 5.4 n.1, at 83.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If28111446b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.,</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304913977" w-serial-number="1994086042" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="I5553a4016b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Kano v. National Consumer Co-op. Bank, 22 F.3d 899 (9th Cir. 1994)</cite.query> ($1,500 sanction for using one-and-one-half-line spacing, rather than double-spacing, and small type for footnotes); <cite.query w-src-number="0304913977" w-serial-number="1991128857" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000344" ID="I5553a4036b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Glass v. IDS Financial Services, Inc., 137 F.R.D. 262 (D. Minn. 1991)</cite.query> (two law firms each fined $50,000 for filing briefs totaling over 2,400 pages).<eos/><bos/> <ital>See also</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304913977" w-serial-number="1987005717" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I5553a4056b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Westinghouse Elec. Corp. v. N.L.R.B., 809 F.2d 419 (7th Cir. 1987)</cite.query> ($1,000 sanction for attempting to evade page limits).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If28138506b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>J.P.M.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913977" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR3.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I555663206b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 3.2(a)(iii)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If28138516b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>J.P.M.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913977" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR3.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I5558fb306b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 3.2(iv)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 4:10<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
